# Summary
A supply-chain hardening bug was introduced by adding a write-capable release workflow that depends on mutable action tags. Pin release actions to audited commit SHAs, preferably minimize token permissions to the exact operations needed, and consider using trusted first-party tooling or verifying action provenance.
The release workflow introduced in this commit runs on release tags and manual dispatch with `contents: write`, then executes `softprops/action-gh-release@v2`. Because the action is referenced by a mutable tag rather than an immutable commit SHA, a compromise of the upstream action repository, action maintainer account, or tag could cause arbitrary code to run in this repository's release workflow with a write-capable GITHUB_TOKEN. That code could create or modify official GitHub releases and upload malicious release assets under the project's trusted release channel. `actions/checkout@v4` is also tag-pinned, but the most security-relevant issue is the third-party release action combined with write permissions.

