## Report
Validated the finding against checked-out commit 9a816fec98b8ea7940509c4a53d08fdec836f21e. Direct crash/Valgrind/debugger validation is not applicable because this is a GitHub Actions supply-chain configuration issue, not a runtime memory-safety bug; targeted enumeration showed the repository contains only documentation and workflow files, and no compiled/executable target was present. gdb and valgrind were also not installed. Evidence: `find . -maxdepth 3 -type f` listed `.github/workflows/ci.yml`, `.github/workflows/release.yml`, `LICENSE`, `README.md`, and `SPEC.md`; `command -v gdb` and `command -v valgrind` returned no paths. The release workflow was introduced by this commit: `git show --name-status HEAD -- .github/workflows/release.yml` showed `A .github/workflows/release.yml`, and `git show HEAD^:.github/workflows/release.yml` failed because the file did not exist in the parent. In `.github/workflows/release.yml`, lines 3-7 trigger the workflow on pushed tags matching `v*`, line 7 enables `workflow_dispatch`, lines 9-10 grant `contents: write`, and lines 26-30 execute `softprops/action-gh-release@v2` to create/upload release artifacts. The `@v2` ref is not an immutable 40-character commit SHA, so the job depends on a mutable third-party action ref while running with a write-capable GITHUB_TOKEN. A validation script confirmed: `tag_trigger=True`, `manual_dispatch=True`, `contents_write_lines=10`, `mutable_action_refs=19:actions/checkout@v4;27:softprops/action-gh-release@v2`, `third_party_release_action_mutably_pinned=27:softprops/action-gh-release@v2`, and `RESULT=VULNERABLE_CONFIGURATION_PRESENT`. This supports the suspected supply-chain hardening bug: if the upstream action/tag or maintainer is compromised, arbitrary action code could run in this release workflow with authority to create/modify GitHub releases and upload assets.

